Symptoms:
- Browser warnings about “Not secure” or “Your connection is not private”
- Certificate errors
- HTTPS not working
- ERR_CERT_AUTHORITY_INVALID

Diagnosis:
grep ssl /opt/docker/nginx/nginx.conf
openssl s_client -connect [service].lab.local:443
ls -la /opt/docker/nginx/certs/
docker logs nginx | grep ssl

Common Causes:
- Self-signed certificate not trusted by browser
- Certificate expired
- Wrong certificate path in Nginx config
- Port 443 not exposed
- Certificate/key file permissions wrong

Solutions:

Generate self-signed certificate:
mkdir -p /opt/docker/nginx/certs
openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048

    keyout /opt/docker/nginx/certs/nginx.key
    out /opt/docker/nginx/certs/nginx.crt
    subj “/CN=*.lab.local”


Update Nginx config:
nano /opt/docker/nginx/nginx.conf

# Add SSL directives to server block:

  server {\\
      listen 443 ssl;\\
      server_name [service].lab.local;\\
      \\
      ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/certs/nginx.crt;\\
      ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/certs/nginx.key;\\
      \\
      location / {\\
          proxy_pass http://[container]:[port];\\
      }\\
  }\\


# Add HTTP to HTTPS redirect:

  server {\\
      listen 80;\\
      server_name [service].lab.local;\\
      return 301 https://$server_name$request_uri;\\
  }\\


Update docker-compose.yml to mount certs:
volumes:

    ./nginx/certs:/etc/nginx/certs:ro


Restart Nginx:
docker compose restart nginx

Trust certificate in browser:
# Browser → Advanced → Accept risk
# Or import cert to system trust store

Prevention:
- Use Let's Encrypt for valid certificates (Phase 2.1)
- Set calendar reminder for cert expiration
- Monitor certificate validity in Grafana
- Document cert renewal procedure

### Browser Shows “Your connection is not private” or Certificate Warning

Symptoms: - Browser displays security warning - Certificate shown as untrusted - “NET::ERR_CERT_AUTHORITY_INVALID” error

Cause: FreeIPA Certificate Authority not trusted on client device

Diagnosis: ```bash # Check certificate issuer openssl s_client -connect service.lab.local:443 | grep “issuer” # Should show: issuer=O=LAB.LOCAL, CN=Certificate Authority ```

Solution:

Download and install FreeIPA CA certificate:

```bash # Download CA cert curl -o ~/ipa-ca.crt http://mgmt.lab.local/ipa/config/ca.crt

# Linux: sudo cp ~/ipa-ca.crt /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/ sudo update-ca-trust

# macOS: sudo security add-trusted-cert -d -r trustRoot -k /Library/Keychains/System.keychain ~/ipa-ca.crt

# Restart browser ```

Prevention: Document CA installation in onboarding procedures

—

### Nginx Shows “cannot load certificate” Error

Symptoms: - Nginx container fails to start - Error in logs: `cannot load certificate “/etc/nginx/ssl/hostname.crt”` - Services inaccessible

Cause: SSL directory not mounted in Docker container

Diagnosis: ```bash # Check if container can see SSL files docker exec nginx ls -la /etc/nginx/ssl/ # If error: mount is missing ```

Solution:

1. Verify volume mount in docker-compose.yml: ```yaml services:

nginx:
  volumes:
    - /etc/nginx/ssl:/etc/nginx/ssl:ro

```

2. Recreate container (restart won't work): ```bash cd /opt/docker docker compose down docker compose up -d ```

3. Verify mount: ```bash docker exec nginx ls -la /etc/nginx/ssl/ # Should show certificate files ```

Prevention: Always recreate containers after docker-compose.yml changes

